referents.fragment: Here comes the shame, here comes the shame

range.content: Here comes the shame, here comes the shame

children: PROPOSED SUGGESTION:
Referring to the “running” in the previous sentence: the feeling of shame is starting to overwhelm you, you’ve metaphorically ran a mile, but you’re too slow… shame is catching up with you.

You’re unable to suppress the memories of the night before: what you have done, what you’ve said and even what you’ve thought. Maybe you went into the night with some great intentions, which you all failed to live up to and now you start to feel ashamed.
Sia begins the song with almost a dubious invincibility, a concept she introduced on her 2008 album
Some People Have Real Problems
. The alcohol shield / IDGAF-barrier makes the party girl immune to feeling anything real… or at least until it wears off.
Alcohol actually does have a numbing effect on the body, and was often used as an anesthetic in the past because it depresses the central nervous system.

From Jesse Shatkin: “Sia and I wrote "Chandelier” on a break from recording her record, in Greg Kurstin’s live room.  It was originally a Marimba and Piano jam session, which turned into an iPhone voice note, which turned into a demo i made at my house, which turned into the final version with Greg’s production that you hear today."

From Greg Kurstin: “‘Chandelier’ was written by Sia and Jesse Shatkin.  Sia brought it in for me to work on and tie into the other songs on the record.  I added some acoustic piano, Mellotron and live drums over the track. I left most of Jesse’s production; which was awesome.”

From Greg Kurstin: “‘Chandelier’ was written by Sia and Jesse Shatkin.  Sia brought it in for me to work on and tie into the other songs on the record.  I added some acoustic piano, Mellotron and live drums over the track. I left most of Jesse’s production; which was awesome.”
Greg Kurstin
is a frequent collaborator of Sia’s. He produced her entire album
We Are Born
and co-wrote several tracks with her. But his hits don’t stop with Sia – he’s worked extensively with
Ellie Goulding
Kelly Clarkson
, Lily Allen and more.

Sia has talked before about her struggles with alcoholism

. Many people believe pushing their worries down with a shot (or two or three) of liquor will make everything better, but she reasons that can be dangerous to keep your emotions suppressed. Not only does it add physical stress on your body, but anything that goes wrong in your life may trigger a release of all that pent up feeling.
